<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08088g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08088g">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08088g"> 88(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> charity i.e. love</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[the]</font> habit &hellip; of using a French word side by side with its native synonym, the latter serving &hellip; as an interpretation of the former for the benefit of those who were not yet familiar with the more refined expression. Thus in the Ancrene Riwle (ab. 1225): <i>cherit&eacute;</i> &thorn;et is <i>luve</i> (p.8) <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 95</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
